'''Speech recognition''' is the  WIKILINK  subfield of  WIKILINK  that develops methodologies and technologies that enables the recognition and  WIKILINK  of spoken language into text by computers. It is also known as '''automatic speech recognition''' ('''ASR'''), '''computer speech recognition''' or '''speech to text''' ('''STT'''). It incorporates knowledge and research in the  WIKILINK ,  WIKILINK , and  WIKILINK  fields.

Some speech recognition systems require \"training\" (also called \"enrollment\") where an individual speaker reads text or isolated  WIKILINK  into the system. The system analyzes the person's specific voice and uses it to fine-tune the recognition of that person's speech, resulting in increased accuracy. Systems that do not use training are called \"speaker independent\" REFERENCE  systems. Systems that use training are called \"speaker dependent\".

Speech recognition applications include  WIKILINK s such as voice dialing (e.g. \"call home\"), call routing (e.g. \"I would like to make a collect call\"),  WIKILINK  appliance control, search (e.g. find a podcast where particular words were spoken), simple data entry (e.g., entering a credit card number), preparation of structured documents (e.g. a radiology report), determining speaker characteristics, REFERENCE  speech-to-text processing (e.g.,  WIKILINK s or  WIKILINK s), and  WIKILINK  (usually termed  WIKILINK ).

{{anchor|vs_voice_rec}}The term ''voice recognition'' NAMEDREF  NAMEDREF  NAMEDREF  or '' LEFTWIKILINK '' REFERENCE  REFERENCE  refers to identifying the speaker, rather than what they are saying.  LEFTWIKILINK  can simplify the task of translating speech in systems that have been trained on a specific person's voice or it can be used to authenticate or verify the identity of a speaker as part of a security process.

From the technology perspective, speech recognition has a long history with several waves of major innovations. Most recently, the field has benefited from advances in  WIKILINK  and  WIKILINK . The advances are evidenced not only by the surge of academic papers published in the field, but more importantly by the worldwide industry adoption of a variety of deep learning methods in designing and deploying speech recognition systems.

==History==
The key areas of growth were: vocabulary size, speaker independence and processing speed.

===Pre-1970===
* '''1952''' – Three Bell Labs researchers, Stephen Balashek, REFERENCE  R. Biddulph, and K. H. Davis built a system called \"Audrey\" REFERENCE  for single-speaker digit recognition. Their system located the  WIKILINK  in the power spectrum of each utterance. REFERENCE
* '''1960''' –  WIKILINK  developed and published the  WIKILINK .
* '''1962''' – IBM demonstrated its 16-word \"Shoebox\" machine's speech recognition capability at the 1962 World's Fair.<ref name=PCW.Siri>{{cite magazine  |magazine=PC World  |accessdate=22 October 2018
