 WIKILINK  was the first person to take on continuous speech recognition as a graduate student at  WIKILINK  in the late 1960s. Previous systems required users to pause after each word. Reddy's system issued spoken commands for playing game  WIKILINK .

Around this time Soviet researchers invented the  WIKILINK  (DTW) algorithm and used it to create a recognizer capable of operating on a 200-word vocabulary. REFERENCE  DTW processed speech by dividing it into short frames, e.g. 10ms segments, and processing each frame as a single unit. Although DTW would be superseded by later algorithms, the technique carried on. Achieving speaker independence remained unsolved at this time period.

