By this point, the vocabulary of the typical commercial speech recognition system was larger than the average human vocabulary.<ref name=\"Communications of the ACM\"/> Raj Reddy's former student,  WIKILINK , developed the  LEFTWIKILINK  system at CMU. The Sphinx-II system was the first to do speaker-independent, large vocabulary, continuous speech recognition and it had the best performance in DARPA's 1992 evaluation. Handling continuous speech with a large vocabulary was a major milestone in the history of speech recognition. Huang went on to found the  LEFTWIKILINK  in 1993. Raj Reddy's student  WIKILINK  joined Apple where, in 1992, he helped develop a speech interface prototype for the Apple computer known as Casper.

 WIKILINK , a Belgium-based speech recognition company, acquired several other companies, including Kurzweil Applied Intelligence in 1997 and Dragon Systems in 2000. The L&H speech technology was used in the  WIKILINK  operating system. L&H was an industry leader until an accounting scandal brought an end to the company in 2001. The speech technology from L&H was bought by ScanSoft which became  LEFTWIKILINK  in 2005.  LEFTWIKILINK  originally licensed software from Nuance to provide speech recognition capability to its digital assistant  WIKILINK . REFERENCE

====2000s====
In the 2000s DARPA sponsored two speech recognition programs: Effective Affordable Reusable Speech-to-Text (EARS) in 2002 and  LEFTWIKILINK  (GALE). Four teams participated in the EARS program:  WIKILINK , a team led by  LEFTWIKILINK  with  WIKILINK  and  LEFTWIKILINK ,
 WIKILINK , and a team composed of  LEFTWIKILINK ,  LEFTWIKILINK  and  WIKILINK . EARS funded the collection of the Switchboard telephone speech corpus containing 260 hours of recorded conversations from over 500 speakers. REFERENCE  The GALE program focused on  LEFTWIKILINK  and  LEFTWIKILINK  broadcast news speech.  WIKILINK 's first effort at speech recognition came in 2007 after hiring some researchers from Nuance. REFERENCE  The first product was  WIKILINK , a telephone based directory service. The recordings from GOOG-411 produced valuable data that helped Google improve their recognition systems.  WIKILINK  is now supported in over 30 languages.

In the United States, the  WIKILINK  has made use of a type of speech recognition for  WIKILINK  since at least 2006. REFERENCE  This technology allows analysts to search through large volumes of recorded conversations and isolate mentions of keywords. Recordings can be indexed and analysts can run queries over the database to find conversations of interest. Some government research programs focused on intelligence applications of speech recognition, e.g. DARPA's EARS's program and  WIKILINK 's  LEFTWIKILINK  program.

In the early 2000s, speech recognition was still dominated by traditional approaches such as  WIKILINK  combined with feedforward  WIKILINK . NAMEDREF
Today, however, many aspects of speech recognition have been taken over by a  WIKILINK  method called  WIKILINK  (LSTM), a  WIKILINK  published by  WIKILINK  &  WIKILINK  in 1997.<ref name=lstm>{{cite journal
   |author1=Sepp Hochreiter    |authorlink1=Sepp Hochreiter
   |author2=J. Schmidhuber  |authorlink2=Jürgen Schmidhuber
   |title=Long Short-Term Memory |journal=Neural Computation|volume=9|issue=8|pages=1735–1780
   |year=1997|doi=10.1162/neco.1997.9.8.1735 |pmid=9377276}}</ref> LSTM RNNs avoid the  WIKILINK  and can learn \"Very Deep Learning\" tasks NAMEDREF  that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps ago, which is important for speech.
Around 2007, LSTM trained by Connectionist Temporal Classification (CTC) NAMEDREF  started to outperform traditional speech recognition in certain applications. NAMEDREF  In 2015, Google's speech recognition reportedly experienced a dramatic performance jump of 49% through CTC-trained LSTM, which is now available through  WIKILINK  to all smartphone users. NAMEDREF

The use of deep feedforward (non-recurrent) networks for  WIKILINK ing was introduced during later part of 2009 by  WIKILINK  and his students at University of Toronto and by Li Deng REFERENCE  and colleagues at Microsoft Research, initially in the collaborative work between Microsoft and University of Toronto which was subsequently expanded to include IBM and Google (hence \"The shared views of four research groups\" subtitle in their 2012 review paper). NAMEDREF  NAMEDREF  In contrast to the steady incremental improvements of the past few decades, the application of deep learning decreased word error rate by 30%.<ref name=\"Scientists-see-advances\"/> This innovation was quickly adopted across the field. Researchers have begun to use deep learning techniques for language modeling as well.

In the long history of speech recognition, both shallow form and deep form (e.g. recurrent nets) of artificial neural networks had been explored for many years during 1980s, 1990s and a few years into the 2000s. NAMEDREF  NAMEDREF  NAMEDREF
But these methods never won over the non-uniform internal-handcrafting  LEFTWIKILINK / WIKILINK  (GMM-HMM) technology based on generative models of speech trained discriminatively. NAMEDREF
A number of key difficulties had been methodologically analyzed in the 1990s, including gradient diminishing NAMEDREF  and weak temporal correlation structure in the neural predictive models. NAMEDREF  NAMEDREF
All these difficulties were in addition to the lack of big training data and big computing power in these early days. Most speech recognition researchers who understood such barriers hence subsequently moved away from neural nets to pursue generative modeling approaches until the recent resurgence of deep learning starting around 2009–2010 that had overcome all these difficulties. Hinton et al. and Deng et al. reviewed part of this recent history about how their collaboration with each other and then with colleagues across four groups (University of Toronto, Microsoft, Google, and IBM) ignited a renaissance of applications of deep feedforward neural networks to speech recognition. NAMEDREF  NAMEDREF  NAMEDREF  NAMEDREF

====2010s====
By early 2010s ''speech'' recognition, also called voice recognition REFERENCE  REFERENCE  REFERENCE  was clearly differentiated from ''sp<u>eaker</u>'' recognition, and speaker independence was considered a major breakthrough. Until then, systems required a \"training\" period.  A 1987 ad for a doll had carried the tagline \"Finally, the doll that understands you.\" – despite the fact that it was described as \"which children could train to respond to their voice\".<ref name=PCW.Siri>{{cite magazine  |magazine=PC World  |accessdate=22 October 2018
